49    /**
50    * Implements a (generalized) LIBOR market model with generic covariance structure (lognormal, normal, displaced or stochastic volatility)
51    * with some drift approximation methods.
52    * <br><br>
53    * In its default case the class specifies a multi-factor LIBOR market model in its log-normal formulation, that is
54    * <i>L<sub>j</sub> = exp(Y<sub>j</sub>) </i> where
55    * \[
56    * dY_{j} = \mu_{j} dt + \lambda_{1,j} dW_{1} + \ldots + \lambda_{m,j} dW_{m}
57    * \]
58    * <br>
59    * The model uses an {@link net.finmath.montecarlo.interestrate.models.covariance.LIBORCovarianceModel} for the specification of
60    * <i>(&lambda;<sub>1,j</sub>,...,&lambda;<sub>m,j</sub>)</i> as a covariance model.
61    * See {@link net.finmath.montecarlo.model.ProcessModel} for details on the implemented interface
62    * <br><br>
63    * However, the class is more general:
64    * <ul>
65    * <li>
66    * The model may be log-normal or normal specification with a given local volatility.
67    * </li>
68    * <li>
69    * The class implements different measure(drift) / numeraire pairs: terminal measure and spot measure.
70    * </li>
71    * <li>
72    * The class allows to configure a discounting curve (e.g.&nbsp;for "OIS discounting") using a simple deterministic zero spread.
73    * In this case, the numeraire \( N(t) \) is adjusted by \( \exp( \int_0^t -\lambda(\tau) d\tau ) \).
74    * </li>
75    * </ul>
76    *
77    * <br>
78    * The class specifies a LIBOR market model, that is
79    * <i>L<sub>j</sub> = f(Y<sub>j</sub>) </i> where
80    * <ul>
81    * <li>
82    * <i>f</i> is <i>f(x) = exp(x)</i> (default, log-normal LIBOR Market Model) or
83    * </li>
84    * <li>
85    * <i>f</i> is <i>f(x) = x</i> (normal model, used if <code>property.set("stateSpace","NORMAL"))</code>
86    * </li>
87    * </ul>
88    * and
89    * <br>
90    * <i>dY<sub>j</sub> = &mu;<sub>j</sub> dt + &lambda;<sub>1,j</sub> dW<sub>1</sub> + ... + &lambda;<sub>m,j</sub> dW<sub>m</sub></i> <br>
91    * <br>
92    * see {@link net.finmath.montecarlo.model.ProcessModel} for details on the implemented interface.
93    * <br>
94    * The model uses an <code>AbstractLIBORCovarianceModel</code> as a covariance model.
95    * If the covariance model is of type <code>AbstractLIBORCovarianceModelParametric</code>
96    * a calibration to swaptions can be performed.
97    * <br>
98    * Note that &lambda; may still depend on <i>L</i>, hence generating a log-normal dynamic for <i>L</i> even
99    * if the stateSpace property has been set to NORMAL.
100    * <br>
101    *
102    * The map <code>properties</code> allows to configure the model. The following keys may be used:
103    * <ul>
104    * <li>
105    * <code>measure</code>: Possible values:
106    * <ul>
107    * <li>
108    * <code>SPOT</code>: Simulate under spot measure. In this case, the single curve numeraire
109    * is \( N(T_{i}) = \prod_{j=0}^{i-1} (1 + L(T_{j},T_{j+1};T_{j}) (T_{j+1}-T_{j})) \).
110    * </li>
111    * <li>
112    * <code>TERMINAL</code>: Simulate under terminal measure. In this case, the single curve numeraire
113    * is \( N(T_{i}) = P(T_{n};T_{i}) = \prod_{j=i}^{n-1} (1 + L(T_{j},T_{j+1};T_{i}) (T_{j+1}-T_{j}))^{-1} \).
114    * </li>
115    * </ul>
116    * </li>
117    * <li>
118    * <code>stateSpace</code>: Possible values:
119    * <ul>
120    * <li>
121    * <code>LOGNORMAL</code>: The state space transform is set to exp, i.e., <i>L = exp(Y)</i>. When the covariance model is deterministic, then this is the classical lognormal LIBOR market model. Note that the covariance model may still provide a local volatility function.
122    * </li>
123    * <li>
124    * <code>NORMAL</code>: The state space transform is set to identity, i.e., <i>L = Y</i>. When the covariance model is deterministic, then this is a normal LIBOR market model. Note that the covariance model may still provide a local volatility function.
125    * </li>
126    * </ul>
127    * </li>
128    * <li>
129    * <code>simulationTimeInterpolationMethod</code>: Possible values:
130    * <ul>
131    * <li>
132    * <code>ROUND_DOWN</code>: \( L(S,T;t) \) is mapped to \( L(S,T,t_{j}) \) with \( t_{j} \) being the largest time in the time discretization such that \( t_{j} \leq t \).
133    * </li>
134    * <li>
135    * <code>ROUND_NEAREST</code>: \( L(S,T;t) \) is mapped to \( L(S,T,t_{j}) \) with \( t_{j} \) being the nearest time in the time discretization.
136    * </li>
137    * </ul>
138    * </li>
139    * <li>
140    * <code>liborCap</code>: An optional <code>Double</code> value applied as a cap to the LIBOR rates.
141    * May be used to limit the simulated valued to prevent values attaining POSITIVE_INFINITY and
142    * numerical problems. To disable the cap, set <code>liborCap</code> to <code>Double.POSITIVE_INFINITY</code>.
143    * </li>
144    * </ul>
145    * <br>
146    * The main task of this class is to calculate the risk-neutral drift and the
147    * corresponding numeraire given the covariance model.
148    *
149    * The calibration of the covariance structure is not part of this class. For the calibration
150    * of parametric models of the instantaneous covariance see
151    * {@link net.finmath.montecarlo.interestrate.models.covariance.AbstractLIBORCovarianceModelParametric#getCloneCalibrated(LIBORMarketModel, CalibrationProduct[], Map)}.
152    *
153    * @author Christian Fries
154    * @version 1.2
155    * @see net.finmath.montecarlo.process.MonteCarloProcess The interface for numerical schemes.
156    * @see net.finmath.montecarlo.model.ProcessModel The interface for models provinding parameters to numerical schemes.
157    * @see net.finmath.montecarlo.interestrate.models.covariance.AbstractLIBORCovarianceModel The abstract covariance model plug ins.
158    * @see net.finmath.montecarlo.interestrate.models.covariance.AbstractLIBORCovarianceModelParametric A parametic covariance model including a generic calibration algorithm.
159    */

1091    /**
1092    * Return the complete vector of the drift for the time index timeIndex, given that current state is realizationAtTimeIndex.
1093    * The drift will be zero for rates being already fixed.
1094    *
1095    * The method currently provides the drift for either <code>Measure.SPOT</code> or <code>Measure.TERMINAL</code> - depending how the
1096    * model object was constructed. For <code>Measure.TERMINAL</code> the j-th entry of the return value is the random variable
1097    * \[
1098    * \mu_{j}^{\mathbb{Q}^{P(T_{n})}}(t) \ = \ - \mathop{\sum_{l\geq j+1}}_{l\leq n-1} \frac{\delta_{l}}{1+\delta_{l} L_{l}(t)} (\lambda_{j}(t) \cdot \lambda_{l}(t))
1099    * \]
1100    * and for <code>Measure.SPOT</code> the j-th entry of the return value is the random variable
1101    * \[
1102    * \mu_{j}^{\mathbb{Q}^{N}}(t) \ = \ \sum_{m(t) &lt; l\leq j} \frac{\delta_{l}}{1+\delta_{l} L_{l}(t)} (\lambda_{j}(t) \cdot \lambda_{l}(t))
1103    * \]
1104    * where \( \lambda_{j} \) is the vector for factor loadings for the j-th component of the stochastic process (that is, the diffusion part is
1105    * \( \sum_{k=1}^m \lambda_{j,k} \mathrm{d}W_{k} \)).
1106    *
1107    * Note: The scalar product of the factor loadings determines the instantaneous covariance. If the model is written in log-coordinates (using exp as a state space transform), we find
1108    * \(\lambda_{j} \cdot \lambda_{l} = \sum_{k=1}^m \lambda_{j,k} \lambda_{l,k} = \sigma_{j} \sigma_{l} \rho_{j,l} \).
1109    * If the model is written without a state space transformation (in its orignial coordinates) then \(\lambda_{j} \cdot \lambda_{l} = \sum_{k=1}^m \lambda_{j,k} \lambda_{l,k} = L_{j} L_{l} \sigma_{j} \sigma_{l} \rho_{j,l} \).
1110    *
1111    *
1112    * @see net.finmath.montecarlo.interestrate.models.LIBORMarketModelFromCovarianceModel#getNumeraire(MonteCarloProcess, double) The calculation of the drift is consistent with the calculation of the numeraire in <code>getNumeraire</code>.
